{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637255"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17646"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17646"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115138"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10360"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17646"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97146"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7741"},{"type":"tags","id":"7745"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24229"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115138"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher wants to study the daily rainfall measurements from a weather station that has collected data for 365 days. They need to select 73 days for detailed analysis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct systematic sampling approach for this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Select every fifth day after randomly choosing day 1-5","Select 73 random days using a random number generator","Select the first 73 days of the year","Select alternate days until reaching 73 samples","Select every fifth day starting from day 1"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct approach is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eselect every fifth day after randomly choosing day 1-5\u003C/strong\u003E. This ensures an unbiased starting point and maintains consistent spacing throughout the sample. The sampling interval (n=5) is calculated by dividing the population size (365) by the desired sample size (73).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelecting 73 random days using a random number generator\u003C/strong\u003E describes simple random sampling, not systematic sampling. \u003Cstrong\u003ESelecting the first 73 days of the year\u003C/strong\u003E introduces seasonal bias by only sampling from one part of the year. \u003Cstrong\u003ESelecting every fifth day starting from day 1\u003C/strong\u003E fails to incorporate the random start needed for systematic sampling. \u003Cstrong\u003ESelecting alternate days until reaching 73 samples\u003C/strong\u003E uses an incorrect sampling interval and would not cover the entire year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESystematic sampling with a random start combines the simplicity of systematic selection with the randomness needed for statistical validity. It works well for this scenario because weather data is naturally ordered by time and unlikely to have a five-day periodicity that could bias the results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Systematic sampling involves selecting every nth item from a population after a random start point.","Systematic sampling is most appropriate when the population is naturally ordered and there is no periodicity in the data.","The sampling interval (n) is calculated by dividing the population size by the desired sample size."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic 